Flow-State is a distributed task scheduling and execution system built in C. Think of it like a simplified version of Apache Airflow — you define a list of jobs and their dependencies, and the system automatically figures out the correct order to run them, sends them to worker machines, runs them, and collects the results.
The system has two programs. The master is the brain — it reads a job definition file, understands which jobs depend on which other jobs, and manages everything. The workers are the hands — they connect to the master, receive a job, actually run it as a real shell script, capture all its output, and report back whether it succeeded or failed.
The jobs are defined in a DAG — a Directed Acyclic Graph. This is just a fancy way of saying "job B cannot start until job A finishes, and job D cannot start until both job B and job C finish." The system enforces this mathematically and guarantees no job runs before its dependencies are complete.
Under the hood, the project demonstrates every major OS concept — processes are created with fork and exec, pipes capture output, signals enforce timeouts, sockets handle network communication between master and workers, mutexes and semaphores prevent race conditions, message queues pipeline log entries, and file locking ensures the log file is written safely.
To answer your friend's question directly — yes, it both schedules AND executes. Scheduling means deciding what runs and when. Execution means actually running the shell script, capturing its output, and handling success or failure. Flow-State does both.

